('513793cc3200603f42d050237ea039432c0ba633', '2014-02-26', '2014-02-27', 'Legals', '<P>5. Citizens request to address council</P><P>No one came forward to speak.</P><P>6. Public hearing to consider a conditional rezoning request from Park Place Investments No. II, LLC for property at 2385 3rd Avenue SW to rezone from R-5 (PUD) to Conditional R-3 (Multi-family Residential)</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained the owners, Park Place Investments No II, LLC, are proposing to sell the property to be developed as Traditions Childrens Center. They are requesting a rezoning for the property from R-5 (PUD) to Conditional R-3 (Multi-family Residential). The condition that staff has suggested and the owner has agreed to, is to limit any multi-family development to no more than 10 units per acre. The reason for the condition is so that if the property were to be redeveloped in the event the day care is sold, the surrounding neighbors would not be subject to a higher density than what was in place when they bought their homes.</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:38pm</P><P>Public Comment: Jon Gruber, 2209 Weatherstone Ct., requested that council wait on allowing any more development in this area until the impact is seen from the new apartment complexes being built. Council Member Dean OConnor explained this development is a child care center. Council Member Kyle Mertz asked for clarification on the conditional zoning. Community Development Director John Shaw explained the conditional zoning would keep the same density as the R-5. Engineer Keith Weggen, Civil Design Advantage, 3405 SE Crossroads, Grimes, representing Park Place Investments and Traditions Childrens Center shared the concept for the child care center. Director Fred Hollister, Eastern Polk County Regional Development, 119 2nd St. SE, spoke in favor of the development.</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:44pm</P><P>7. Ordinance to consider conditional rezoning request from Park Place Investments No. II, LLC for property at 2385 3rd Avenue SW to rezone from R-5 (PUD) to Conditional R-3 (Multi-family Residential) (1st Reading)</P><P>Ordinance No. 2-17-2014 #01 (387) TO CONSIDER CONDITIONAL REZONING REQUEST FROM PARK PLACE INVESTMENTS NO. II, LLC FOR PROPERTY AT 2385 3RD AVENUE SW TO REZONE FROM R-5 (PUD) TO CONDITIONAL R-3 (MULTI-FAMILY RESIDENTIAL)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (1st reading):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To waive 2nd & 3rd reading):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To publish):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>8. Public hearing to consider approving plans, specs and forms of contract for Water Plant #2 Painting</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained the City received competitive quotations for the Water Plant No. 2 Painting Project on February 4, 2014. The engineers estimate for this project was $95,000. Three competitive quotations were received with the low of $55,386 to a high of $123,600. The low quote was submitted by Mongan Painting Company, Inc. from Cherokee, Iowa.</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:47pm</P><P>Public Comment: No one came forward to speak.</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:48pm</P><P>9. Resolution to approve the plans, specifications, form of contract and estimated costs for Water Plant #2 Painting</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #01 TO APPROVE THE PLANS, SPECIFICATIONS, FORM OF CONTRACT AND ESTIMATED COSTS FOR WATER PLANT #2 PAINTING</P><P>Council Member OConnor asked since the low bid was rather low compared to the engineers cost was the company capable of handling this job.</P><P>Engineer Brent Culp, Snyder and Associates, 2121 Synder Blvd., Ankeny, responded that the company understands the scope and requirements of the job.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor 2 Sloan (5-0)</P><P>10. Resolution to approve the contract and bond for Water Plant #2 Painting</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #02 TO APPROVE THE CONTRACT AND BOND FOR WATER PLANT #2 PAINTING</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor 2 Sloan (5-0)</P><P>11.Resolution making the award of the contract for Water Plant #2 Painting</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #03 MAKING THE AWARD OF THE CONTRACT FOR WATER PLANT #2 PAINTING</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained our engineer is recommending the award of the contract for Water Plant No. 2 Painting Project to Mongan Painting Company, Inc. from Cherokee, Iowa in the amount of $55,386.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor 2 Sloan (5-0)</P><P>12. Public hearing to consider approving plans, specs and forms of contract for 12th Ave. Water Main & Footing Drain Improvements Program</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained on February 6, 2014, the City received bids for the 12th Avenue NW Water Main and Footing Drain Collector Improvement Project. Four bids were received ranging from a low of $536,372 to a high of $851,215. The engineers estimate was $683,000. The low bid was submitted by Synergy Contracting, LLC from Bondurant, Iowa.</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:49pm</P><P>Public Comment: No one came forward to comment</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:50pm</P><P>13. Resolution to approve the plans, specifications, form of contract and estimated costs for 12th Ave. Water Main & Footing Drain Improvements Program</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #04 TO APPROVE THE PLANS, SPECIFICATIONS, FORM OF CONTRACT AND ESTIMATED COSTS FOR 12TH AVE. WATER MAIN & FOOTING DRAIN IMPROVEMENTS PROGRAM</P><P>Council Member OConnor asked about Synergys previous work in the city. Mr. Culp, Snyder and Associates, shared that city had additions to the last project and Synergy completed the work under engineers cost expectations.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor 2 Sloan (5-0)</P><P>14. Resolution to approve the contract and bond for 12th Ave. Water Main & Footing Drain Improvements Program</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #05 TO APPROVE THE CONTRACT AND BOND FOR 12TH AVE. WATER MAIN & FOOTING DRAIN IMPROVEMENTS PROGRAM</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor 2 Sloan (5-0)</P><P>15. Resolution making the award of the contract for 12th Ave. Water Main & Footing Drain Improvements Program</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #06 MAKING THE AWARD OF THE CONTRACT FOR 12TH AVE. WATER MAIN & FOOTING DRAIN IMPROVEMENTS PROGRAM</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained our engineer is recommending the award of the contract to Synergy Contracting, LLC in the amount of $536,372.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor 2 Sloan (5-0)</P><P>16.Public hearing to consider amendments to City of Altoona Code of Ordinances Chapter 17 (Council)</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained this is a public hearing to amend the Code of Ordinances, Chapter 17.03.</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:53pm</P><P>Public Comment: No one came forward to speak.</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:54pm</P><P>17. Ordinance to amend the 2004 City of Altoona Code of Ordinances Chapter 17 (Council) (1st Reading)</P><P>Ordinance No. 2-17-2014 #02 (388) TO AMEND THE 2004 CITY OF ALTOONA CODE OF ORDINANCES CHAPTER 17 (COUNCIL)</P><P>City Administrator Jeff Mark explained our code needs to reflect the new statutory threshold of $100,000. Currently, our code reads $25,000.</P><P>Roll Call Vote (1st reading):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer 1 Mertz Y OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To waive 2nd & 3rd reading):</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 1 Mertz 2 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To publish):</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 1 Mertz 2 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>18. Continue Public Hearing to consider an ordinance amendment to consider changes to the development standards of Chapter 168.13 C-7 (Regional Commercial)</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained staff has been working with the developer, Heart of America, to create a unique regional commercial attraction. Director Shaw explained the development plan called a Design Review Manual (DRM). It generally describes uses for the entire Prairie Crossing development, but it mainly focuses on the Waterside Entertainment Territory (WET). The DRM lays out the requirements for architectural and landscaping standards. The standards are tailored to a prairie theme for both the architecture and landscaping. The ordinance leaves the approval of the architecture and landscaping up to a DRM review by the developer, with P&Z review and ultimately the approval of the City Council.</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:54pm</P><P>Public Comment: No one came forward to speak.</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:55pm</P><P>19. Ordinance to consider amending Chapter 168.13 C-7 (Regional Commercial) (1st Reading)</P><P>Ordinance No. 2-17-2014 #03 (389) TO CONSIDER AMENDING CHAPTER 168.13 C-7 (REGIONAL COMMERCIAL)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (1st reading):</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 2 Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To waive 2nd & 3rd reading):</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 2 Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To publish):</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 2 Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>20. Continue Public Hearing to consider an ordinance amendment to Chapter 171.01(2) (K) regarding the architectural design standards of the C-7 zoning district</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained this amendment removes the architectural design requirement of 60% brick/stone/tilts up from the C-7 language and stipulates that the approval of the architectural design is up to the DRM review by the developer, the review of P&Z, and the approval of the City Council.</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:56pm</P><P>Public Comment: No came forward to speak.</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:57pm</P><P>21. Ordinance to consider amending Chapter 171.01(2) (K) regarding the architectural design standards of the C-7 zoning district (1st Reading)</P><P>Ordinance No. 2-17-2014 #04 (390) TO CONSIDER AMENDING CHAPTER 171.01(2) (K) REGARDING THE ARCHITECTURAL DESIGN STANDARDS OF THE C-7 ZONING DISTRICT</P><P>Director Shaw explained this establishes the C-7 district in the architectural design code rather than being lumped together with all commercial developments.</P><P>Roll Call Vote (1st reading):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To waive 2nd & 3rd reading):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>Roll Call Vote (To publish):</P><P>2 Boka Y Harmeyer Y Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>22. Public Hearing to consider a development plan for Prairie Crossing</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained this is a public hearing to consider the approval of the development plan for Prairie Crossing. Director Shaw explained the property is zoned C-7 (Regional Commercial). The development plan lays out how the 175 acre property will be split into territories. Although this proposed plan explains the general guidelines for the entire Shoppes at Prairie Crossing development and the common elements for the entire larger property, a specific Design Review Manual will be created for each territory. The first territory is the Waterside Entertainment Territory or "WET".</P><P>Open Hearing at 6:58pm</P><P>Public Comment: No one came forward to speak.</P><P>Closed Hearing at 6:59pm</P><P>23. Resolution to consider approval of a development plan for Prairie Crossing</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #07 TO CONSIDER APPROVAL OF A DEVELOPMENT PLAN FOR PRAIRIE CROSSING</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 2 Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>24. Resolution to consider approval of a preliminary plat for Prairie Crossing Plat 2</P><P>City Administrator Mark explained the developer is still working on a solution to the deck/patio extending out over the lake. The lot that Johnnys sits on is a different lot than the lake is on. The developer is seeking a remedy to this issue that will allow the restaurant and the deck/patio to be connected. At the time the developer had not submitted the legal paperwork. Council Member Mertz motioned to table the preliminary plat until the legal documents are submitted and Bob Laden has had an opportunity to review.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 1 Mertz 2 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>25. Resolution to consider approval of a final plat for Prairie Crossing Plat 2</P><P>Council Member Mertz motioned to table the final plat until the legal documents are submitted and Bob Laden has had an opportunity to review.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 1 Mertz 2 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>26. Resolution to consider approval of a site plan for Johnnys Italian Steakhouse</P><P>Council Member Mertz motioned to table the site plan until the legal documents are submitted and Bob Laden has had an opportunity to review.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 1 Mertz 2 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>27. Resolution to consider approval of a site plan for Iowa Donor Network Services</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #08 TO CONSIDER APPROVAL OF A SITE PLAN FOR IOWA DONOR NETWORK SERVICES</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained Iowa Donor Network Services, is seeking site plan approval for their facility located at 320 Adventureland Drive NW. Engineer Jason Mathas, Shive Hattery, 1601 48th St # 200, West Des Moines, representing Iowa Donor Network Services explained they are proposing to construct a 17,970 square foot, one story building on 3.4 acres. An overhead door faces north toward a public street and required a variance from the Board of Adjustment, which was approved on February 13, 2014. Angie Capps of the Iowa Donor Network,8191 Birchwood Ct., Suite A, Johnston, gave some background on the services provided and their expectations for this facility.</P><P>Roll Call Vote:</P><P>Y Boka Y Harmeyer 2 Mertz 1 OConnor Y Sloan (5-0)</P><P>28. Resolution to consider approval of a site plan for Dayton Freight</P><P>Resolution 2-17-2014 #09 TO CONSIDER APPROVAL OF A SITE PLAN FOR DAYTON FREIGHT</P><P>Mayor Conkling explained Dayton Freight Lines, Inc. is seeking site plan approval for their facility located at 1501 11th, Avenue NW, in the NE Industrial Park. They are proposing to construct a trucking terminal for Dayton Freight, a Midwest Freight carrier. The terminal building is 24,310 square feet, including 3,919 square feet of office space and a 6,000 square foot maintenance building will also be constructed on the site. The site is a corner lot and as such one half of the overhead doors will face the public street. This required a variance from the Board of Adjustment which was granted on February 13, 2014.</P><P>Roll Call Vote: </P><P>\n  '),
