('55b8f28ce987d473a28435662e31dfdd8a145016', '2014-02-26', '2014-02-27', 'Legals', 'RTIES IN POSSESSION,</P><P>Defendants.</P><P>TO THE ABOVE-NAMED DEFENDANTS:</P><P>You are hereby notified that there is now on file in the Office of the Clerk of the above Court, a Petition, in the above-entitled action which prays for judgment in rem and in the principal amount of $60,239.48 plus interest to 12/17/2013 in the amount of $1,581.30, and thereafter at the rate of 5.2% per annum, such amount equaling $263.55 per day, the costs of the action including report of title costs $250.00, escrow advance of $807.92, other fees of $49.10, late charges of $42.30, and reasonable attorney fees and that said sums be declared a lien upon the following-described premises at 204 Titus Ave., Des Moines, Polk County, Iowa, to-wit:</P><P>Lot 17 in Farr Addition Plat 2, an Official Plat, now included in and forming a part of the City of Des Moines, Polk County, Iowa;</P><P>that the mortgage on the above-described real estate be foreclosed; that a special execution issue for the sale of as much of the mortgaged premises as is necessary to satisfy the judgment; and for other relief as the Court may deem just and equitable. The attorney for the Plaintiff is Brian G. Sayer, of the law firm of Klatt, Odekirk, Augustine, Sayer, Treinen & Rastede, P.C., whose address is 531 Commercial Street, Suite 250; P.O. Box 2675, Waterloo, IA 50704-2675, telephone (319) 232-3304, facsimile (319) 232-3639.</P><P>NOTICE</P><P>THE PLAINTIFF HAS ELECTED FORECLOSURE WITHOUT REDEMPTION. THIS MEANS THAT THE SALE OF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY WILL OCCUR PROMPTLY AFTER ENTRY OF JUDGMENT UNLESS YOU FILE WITH THE COURT A WRITTEN DEMAND TO DELAY THE SALE. IF YOU FILE A WRITTEN DEMAND, THE SALE WILL BE DELAYED UNTIL SIX MONTHS FROM ENTRY OF JUDGMENT IF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY IS YOUR RESIDENCE AND IS A ONE-FAMILY OR TWO-FAMILY DWELLING OR UNTIL TWO MONTHS FROM ENTRY OF JUDGMENT IF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY IS NOT YOUR RESIDENCE OR IS YOUR RESIDENCE BUT NOT A ONE-FAMILY OR TWO-FAMILY DWELLING. YOU WILL HAVE NO RIGHT OF REDEMPTION AFTER THE SALE. THE PURCHASER AT THE SALE WILL BE ENTITLED TO IMMEDIATE POSSESSION OF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY. YOU MAY PURCHASE AT THE SALE.</P><P>IF YOU DO NOT FILE A WRITTEN DEMAND TO DELAY THE SALE AND IF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY IS YOUR RESIDENCE AND IS A ONE-FAMILY OR TWO-FAMILY DWELLING, THEN A DEFICIENCY JUDGMENT WILL NOT BE ENTERED AGAINST YOU. IF YOU DO FILE A WRITTEN DEMAND TO DELAY THE SALE, THEN A DEFICIENCY JUDGMENT MAY BE ENTERED AGAINST YOU IF THE PROCEEDS FROM THE SALE OF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY ARE INSUFFICIENT TO SATISFY THE AMOUNT OF THE MORTGAGED DEBT AND COSTS.</P><P>IF THE MORTGAGED PROPERTY IS NOT YOUR RESIDENCE OR IS NOT A ONE-FAMILY OR TWO-FAMILY DWELLING, THEN A DEFICIENCY JUDGMENT MAY BE ENTERED AGAINST YOU WHETHER OR NOT YOU FILE A WRITTEN DEMAND TO DELAY THE SALE.</P><P>You are further notified that unless you serve and, within a reasonable time thereafter, file a motion or answer on or before the 1st day of April, 2014, in the Iowa District Court for Polk County, Iowa, at the Courthouse in Des Moines, Iowa, judgment by default will be rendered against you for the relief demanded in the Petition.</P><P>If you need assistance to participate in court due to a disability, call the disability coordinator at 515-286-3184. Persons who are hearing or speech impaired may call Relay Iowa TTY (1-800-735-2942). Disability coordinators cannot provide legal advice.</P><P>Clerk of Court</P><P>Polk County Courthouse</P><P>Des Moines, Iowa</P><P>IMPORTANT: YOU ARE ADVISED TO SEEK LEGAL ADVICE AT ONCE TO PROTECT YOUR INTERESTS. </P>\n  '),
('57f87fcf88eefddf0a2860721f1655ad61c7e8ef', '2014-02-26', '2014-02-27', 'Legals', '\n    <P><B> CITY OF ALTOONA COUNCIL WORKSESSION </B></P><P><B> MONDAY, FEBRUARY 10, 2014, 6:30 P.M. </B></P><P><B> AT THE ALTOONA CITY HALL </B></P><P> 1. CALL TO ORDER</P><P>2. Discuss Heart of America Development Issues</P><P>A) C-7 zoning ordinance amendments</P><P>B) Architectural design standards ordinance amendment</P><P>C) Prairie Crossing Development Plan</P><P>D) Prairie Crossing Plat 2</P><P>E) Johnnys Italian Steakhouse site plan</P><P>John Shaw presented to the mayor and council all the information related to the Prairie Crossing Development. Mayor and council asked questions about architectural design standards and the landscaping plan. John explained that city staff was comfortable moving forward with what has been agreed to with the Heart of America staff. Mayor and council asked staff to continue to move project forward.</P><P>3. Discuss Community Garden Project - Terry Henkel from the Altoona Healthy Partnership presented the idea of a community garden. She explained the proposed locations, grants they are applying for and some of the rules that would apply. Mayor and council are excited about the idea and thanked Terry for all of her hard work on this project.</P><P>4. Discuss Enabling Garden Project - Jeff Mark shared with mayor and council the proposed plans for the Enabling Garden. After discussing the mayor and council were good with the proposed plans.</P><P>5. Discuss Sewer Backup Issue - Jeff Mark discussed with mayor and council the sewer backup issue. Mayor and council asked Jeff to contact the homeowner and tell them that they need to file a claim with their homeowner insurance company before council will consider any action.</P><P>6. Discuss Altoona Chamber Request for Funding - Mayor and council agreed to keep the funding level for the chamber the same as current year. ($7,000.00)</P><P>7. Discuss City of Bondurant Inspection Issue - Jeff Mark explained that the City of Bondurant had received a bid from V & K to do inspection services. Mayor and council are in agreement to let V & K take over the City of Bondurant inspection services.</P><P>8. Other Business - None</P><P>9. Adjourn - 1st - Mertz, 2nd - Sloan, Y-Boka, Y-Harmeyer, Y- OConnor, (5-0) Time: 7:35 p.m.</P><P>Randy Pierce, City Clerk</P><P>J.M. Skip Conkling, Mayor </P>\n  '),
('588278824d52922cf1d4842bd99d9dc08bdf21cf', '2014-02-26', '2014-02-27', 'Legals', '3 p.m.</P><P>2. ROLL CALL</P><P>Present: Clabaugh, Lindeman, Brown, Cope</P><P>Absent: Temple</P><P>Council Member Brown arrived at 5:38 p.m.</P><P>3. DISCUSSION WITH JOHNSTON COMMUNITY SCHOOL BOARD</P><P>a. Update on the planning for the new high school and other building improvements</P><P>Superintendent Guthmiller provided an overview on the building projects within the district.</P><P>b. Report on the status and timing of improvements to the roads that serve the new high school</P><P>City Administrator Jim Sanders outlined the scheduled road projects throughout the city, including those being undertaken by Iowa Department of Transportation. Sanders noted that in some instances the road improvements were joint projects with other entities. He also advised that project schedules were being set that would minimize traffic impacts to residents and the school district.</P><P>c. Update on proposed traffic disruptions/road closures planned over the next several years</P><P>Addressed under item 3B.</P><P>d. Discuss status of elementary school boundary revisions and school walk zones.</P><P>Guthmiller noted that the options for the new boundaries had been narrowed to two options, with the final decision scheduled to be decided at the School Boards February 24 meeting.</P><P>Members discussed the potential impact of boundary changes to the districts walk zones. There was also a brief discussion regarding the districts bus program and potential changes in the future.</P><P>e. Update on the School Resource Officer Program</P><P>Chief of Police Bill Vaughn provided an update on the SRO program and briefed the Board and Council on ongoing safety measures being handled by the Police Department.</P><P>f. Update on the Public Safety Buildings</P><P>Chief Vaughn and Fire Chief Jim Krohse provided an update on the building project. Chief Krohse also provided an update on fire department activity; including the impact the new west side station is having in the community.</P><P>g. Discuss opportunities to share programs and resources between the school district and city.</P><P>Guthmiller and Sanders noted that both were pleased with the communication between the district and the city as both entities were always looking for partnering opportunities.</P><P>h. Report on the Tax Increment Financing program</P><P>Sanders reviewed the TIF program and the impact it has had on the community.</P><P>i. Other discussion items</P><P>Council and Board members noted the importance of a continued partnership and their desire to continue to have joint meetings.</P><P>The meeting adjourned at 6:42 p.m.</P><P>Paula S. Dierenfeld, Mayor</P><P>ATTEST:</P><P>Cyndee D. Rhames, City Clerk </P>\n  '),
